    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. An escrow account is a financial arrangement where a third party, known as an escrow agent, holds and regulates the payment of the funds required for two parties involved in a given transaction. In the context of a house purchase, the escrow agent is typically a bank or a title company.\n\nThe role of the escrow agent is to ensure that the buyer's funds are safe and that the seller's property is transferred only when all the terms of the sale are met. The escrow agent will hold the buyer's down payment, closing costs, and any other agreed-upon funds in the escrow account. They will also ensure that the seller's property title is clear and that any other conditions of the sale, such as inspections or repairs, are fulfilled.\n\nOnce all the conditions are met, the escrow agent will release the funds to the seller and facilitate the transfer of the property title to the buyer. This process helps to protect both parties and ensures a smooth and fair transaction.",
