    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, the escrow agent acts as a neutral middleman to ensure fairness and security in the transaction. To make sure everything goes smoothly and your money is properly handled during the closing, here are a few things to watch out for:\n\n1. **Closing Statement**: Review the closing statement carefully. It should itemize all the costs and fees associated with the purchase, including the down payment, closing costs, and any other expenses. Make sure these are accurate and that there are no unexpected charges.\n\n2. **Title Insurance**: Ensure that you have title insurance, which protects you from any future claims against the property title. This is a crucial step in safeguarding your investment.\n\n3. **Property Inspection**: If you haven't already, have a professional inspection of the property to identify any potential issues. This can save you from unexpected repairs and costs after the purchase.\n\n4. **Final Walk-Through**: Conduct a final walk-through of the property with your real estate agent before closing. This allows you to verify that the property is in the agreed-upon condition and that any promised repairs have been completed.\n\n5. **Communication with the Escrow Agent**: Stay in regular contact with your escrow agent. They can provide updates on the status of",
